Figures and Tables

Automatic numbering and cross-referencing

Figures and tables can be automatically numbered by entering label: fig-somename or label: tbl-somename in the R-chunk header. You can create links in the text by referring to these labels using @fig-somename or @tbl-somename.

How to make a figure caption

(fig-example?) is an illustration of the method to make captions with the fig-cap option in th R-chunk header.

library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data=iris, mapping=aes(x=Petal.Width, y=Petal.Length, colour=Species)) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  labs(x="Petal width (mm)", y="Petal length (mm)", colour="Iris species")

This caption is in italics .You can also use normal font.

You can put multiple sub-figures in one tableau, see examples on the Quarto website.

Size of figures

Controlling the size of figures can be frustrating if you do not understand the parameters that determine size. There are four parameters that affect size: fig-width, fig-height, out-width and out-height. The first two parameters determine the size of the plotting device, whereas the third and fourth parameters determine the degree to which this plotting device is scaled in the document. I usually set the defaults by setting the global knitting parameters in the first R-chunk: knitr::opts_chunk$set(fig.width=5, fig.height=5, out.width='50%', fig.align='center'). In Quarto documents you can also put these global settings in the top yaml section under the execute sub-section, see the Quarto documentation. This leads to the following output:

Decreasing to fig-width: 3 and fig-height: 3 decreases the size of the plotting device, but not the font size and size of other graphical elements in that device. The smaller device is subsequently enlarged to the same size as above because the out-width (and out-height) is the same:

When making figures with other proportions you will usually want to adapt fig-width or fig-height as well as out-width, as in the case below where I plot two figures next to each other using the patchwork package and with chunk settings fig-width: 10, fig-height: 5, out-width: 100%:

## Error in install.packages : Updating loaded packages

Making tables with header caption

You can make tables using the kable() function from the knitr package, or more beautiful even, using the functions from the kableExtra package. First install the latter package before continuing.

Below, both methods are illustrated.

In (tbl-kable?) we use the kable() function from the knitr package to make a table and, if needed, adapted column names.

knitr::kable(iris[1:5,],
             col.names=c("Sepal length", "Sepal width", "Petal length", "Petal width", "Species"),
             format="html")
Sepal length Sepal width Petal length Petal width Species
5.1 3.5 1.4 0.2 setosa
4.9 3.0 1.4 0.2 setosa
4.7 3.2 1.3 0.2 setosa
4.6 3.1 1.5 0.2 setosa
5.0 3.6 1.4 0.2 setosa


The output of the kable() function can be styled using functions from the kableExtra package. In (tbl-kableextra?) we use the kable_classic() styling function. Others are kable_classic_2(), kable_material(), kable_material_dark(), etc. See “Alternative HTML themes” in the help for the kableExtra package.

knitr::kable(iris[1:5,],
             col.names=c("Sepal length", "Sepal width", "Petal length", "Petal width", "Species"),
             format="html") |>
kableExtra::kable_classic(full_width=FALSE)
Sepal length Sepal width Petal length Petal width Species
5.1 3.5 1.4 0.2 setosa
4.9 3.0 1.4 0.2 setosa
4.7 3.2 1.3 0.2 setosa
4.6 3.1 1.5 0.2 setosa
5.0 3.6 1.4 0.2 setosa

Generate the html output of this document by pushing the Knit button in Rstudio.

Making bibliographic citations

How to include bibliographic citations is explained on the Quarto website. Briefly, you need a file with the cited literature, put the path of that file in the YAML header of the document under the section bibliography as demonstrated in the YAML header of this file. Subsequently you can cite in the text using the syntax explained on the quarto website.

You can also modify the citation style using a CSL file, however the default citation style is usually OK. The bibliography file can be provided in Bibtex or BibLatex, JSON, YAML or RIS, see the pandoc manual. With this template you will find a bibtex file literature/A1.bib.

In this assignment you will probably want to cite Venn-Watson and co-workers (2020).

2.Study the data in the two excel files from the PNAS paper (Venn-Watson, Jensen, and Schork 2020) and describe their redundancies and how you would solve these (i.e. which tables would you make to resolve redundancies). What is in general the problem with redundancies?

Answer_2: Based on Based on the feature columns, it appears that the data includes information on the animals’ demographic information (AnimalID, sex, species, age, reason), laboratory measures (fasting, Labcode), and a range of hematological, biochemical, and metabolic parameters. Redundancy in a dataset means that there is either duplicate or overlapping information present in the data, which can lead to data inconsistencies and errors, as well as increased storage requirements and slower query processing times.

In this case, it can be observed that the values of the attribute “Reason, Fasting” are being repeated, and the “Labcode” is not required for data analysis. The first file includes information on animal ID, species, and age, and another table also includes information on animal ID and species but with different age values, so this is redundancy in the data.

To resolve these redundancies, I will make the age column in sd01 keep the same format as sd02.

Answer 6: The average age of wild dolphins is 20 y, Navy dolphins live an average of 32.5 y. And the criteria used by author is 10-40 y.from the histogram of sd01 of the age, we can see the majority age is 10-35 and for For wild bottlenose dolphins 25 years is old. So, my objective selection criteria for membership of the Mid age group is 10-30.

Answer_9:

library(ggplot2)
mid_age = subset(sd01_new,sd01_new$Age>=10&sd01_new$Age<=40)
#mid_age
hemo =sd01_new[,c("Age","Sex","HGB")]
#hemo
female_hemo=subset(hemo, hemo$Sex=="F")
#female_hemo
male_hemo=subset(hemo, hemo$Sex=="M")
ggplot(hemo, aes(Age, y=HGB,color=Sex))+
  geom_line()+
  geom_smooth(method = "lm",se=FALSE)+
  facet_wrap(~Sex,nrow = 1)+
   labs(title="Hemoglobin Content vs Mid Age Group by Sex",
       x="Mid Age Group",
       y="Hemoglobin Content")

The resulting graph shows that females generally have lower hemoglobin content than males at all mid age groups, suggesting that the authors’ conclusion that females apparently age faster than most males when taking into account hemoglobin content only is valid.
